# Internet of Things Infrastructure & Security

## Smart, intelligent and connected
The world is buzzing around the Internet of Things. Everything is becoming smart, intelligent and connected from cups  that make sure you hydrate intelligently, pets , diapers  and even complete smart cities .  With the rise of popularity of microcontrollers like the Arduino, the Maker Movement seems to become an infinite source of creativity. While not all new connected devices will turn out to be useful or relevant in the long term, this IoT trend has started and is already impacting the way we interact with our houses with products like the Amazon Echo  and smart lightbulbs or how we play sports and exercise with one of many of the  fitness trackers.

Also the industry is embracing this trend with applications across the domain of energy to fully optimize the use of your energy grid, health to monitor our wellness, automotive to enable safe self-driving cars and off course smart manufacturing to optimize production. Cities are looking into IoT to optimize transportation, waste management, safety, etc. Juniper  predicts that the number of connected IoT (Internet of Things) devices, sensors and actuators will reach over 46 billion in 2021. 

## Connectivity for IoT
Although more factors drive the Internet of Things, like the advancements in microcontrollers and artificial intelligence, wireless connectivity is one of the enablers of the Internet of Thigs. Wireless protocols range from short range like Bluetooth, Zigbee, Z-Wave and WiFi to long range technologies like satellite communication and Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN). Short range wireless are often used in home automation or for personal devices. 
Long range wireless technologies like (LPWAN) have existed for quite a while, but only these last year are being discovered by makers with the popularity of  of LoRa  and SigFox . LPWAN has a limited bandwidth and the devices are only allowed to send a limited number of message each day, but they are very power efficient and can sometimes run for a couple of years on batteries. These features make them ideal for sensor networks, for example to measure air quality or track bicycles.  

LoRa, a LPWAN example,  is interesting because it uses an unlicensed radio spectrum, it allows makers to create their own IoT infrastructure with just a Raspberry Pi  without  the need of a paid subscription from a mobile operator. Initiatives like The Things Network  plan to build a global network infrastructure by providing cheap gateways, open-source firmware and encourage and facilitate their community in building applications with tutorials, YouTube videos and code on GitHub.  

This trend has not been overlooked by the telecom industry, several mobile operators are readying their own LoRa network or focussing on NarrowBand  IoT  (NB-IoT) a licenced alternative that for some mobile operators requires just a software update for their existing infrastructure. On the long term 5G, the next standard for mobile wireless communication, also specifically provides solutions for IoT communication. 

## Will it be safe?
As we are entering the era of Internet of Things, we get surrounded by devices that have access to home or company networks. With several recent incidents, like the attack on internet infrastructure company Dyn , it is clear that these devices can pose a threat not only to the integrity of these networks15 but also to critical internet infrastructures. Not many consumers are aware of these vulnerabilities as they buy their new television, smart light bulb, door lock or fitness bracelet. With many different network and communication protocols, suppliers and products are all competing in the same market. At the same time security has been not been highest priority. With possible severe consequences, experts      urge all stakeholders (manufactures, legislators and users) to come up with regulations and enhance the cybersecurity awareness.

_Trend.Description: # Biofabrication and smart materials Materials are developing even faster than the machines for digital manufacturing. Material science is not a new trend, but in the near past, a lot of new material have reached the market for small 3D printers. This progress is presumed to be led by the wide distribution of small and affordable printers in every school and lab around the world. This is only expecting to grow faster. Here is a good overview of the normal materials for [FDM printing](https://all3dp.com/best-3d-printer-filament-types-pla-abs-pet-exotic-wood-metal/). Biofabriaction is one of the innovations in new 3D printing techniques and materials that could potentially have a big impact on the medical world. In labs around the world researchers are also working it. ## Biofabrication Biofabrication is the automatic combination and assembly of cells, biochemical or other scaffolding structures to produce tissues (in 2D) or organs (in 3D). This field is the natural evolution of tissue engineering research with cells and stem cells, which is now going toward 3 dimensions and full automation of the process. This field is very active in term of research and the first clinical implementation for bladder fabrication is already available. The time horizon for many more application is 2-10 years. ## Lifetime extension and quality enhancement Biofabrication brings the opportunity to create customized human spare parts, answering a huge need for organ transplant as well as making the medication need after transplant irrelevant as the organs are made fully biocompatible using the patient own cells. Anyone in the general public, who need an organ spare part, will likely be able to "order it" and have it produced from a "Bioprinter". In short the opportunity is lifetime extension and life quality enhancement. It also brings the possibility to “upgrade” itself with better body parts. Biofabrication evolution is likely to meet with biomechatronic science and create a new field of cybernetic organism (cyborg) and biological- computer interfaces such as Neuralink . When engineering humans, ethical question come into consideration, as soon as the possibility for body enhancement will be available to many, there will certainly be regulation by countries that will define what can be done or not. Also the very regulated processes in the field of medicine will certainly create quite some delay between the technology ready for use and the wide adoption of the technology to the masses. Existing biotechnology companies might find a lot of inspiration by this trend and by using their existing experience will be able to innovate in the field. New biotech companies will have the opportunities to innovate in the field with minimum investment needed. It is also a field that will most likely not be affected by any sort of financial crisis, with a very strong value proposition. The equipment needed to start biofabrication is becoming cheap and accessible to all. Makers are already practicing what is called Biohacking (biofabrication by makers), by doing so biohackers might be the one to create the first biotechnologies company on the market with concrete application of biofabrication. ## 4D printing and smart materials Another concept that is related to smart materials trend is 4D printing: 3D printed structures that can change to a “pre-programmed” shape by some kind of external change in the environment. This is possible with “smart materials”. These materials can be effected by either current, temperature, water or other chemical impact. The term also refers to self-assembly of several parts into one part printed in multi-material impacted by e.g. a shake to transform it-self into a new shape. So either the material or each part of the assembly can be “programmed” to act (bend, change size etc.) in a certain way, transforming into a new geometry. 4D printing is a relative new concept, and have so far found very few actual applications. The potential is unpredictable, and MIT have a self-Assembly Lab dedicated to this with Skylar Tibbits talking about a self-assembly world. For instance, an idea is that valves in flow systems can close and open at specific temperatures and underground pipes can repair them self by expanding and closing holes, cracks etc. when exposed to water or the whole system of pipes can adapt to an increased demand. Another creative thought is that buildings in the future with smart materials will change shape or function by water and heat to in order to increase comfort inside. Materials for a regular FDM printer could soon be ￼available to makers and other tinkerers. ￼It's hard to tell what real applications there will be for 4D printing but the researchers in Centre of Excellence for Electromaterials Science , Australia, is currently working on a hand for robotic prosthetics. The hand is made with 3d printed smart materials that will respond to impulses from the brain via an interfaces on the users muscles.

_Trend.Description: # Virtual Currencies & Blockchain A virtual currency is digital money that is not issued by a bank or a public authority, but which is accepted as mean of electronic payment. Historically virtual currencies were issued and used within the limit of a specific virtual community but the success of cryptocurrencies like bitcoins (seen as a safe asset) made such currencies real alternative to classical currencies. Cryptocurrencies are powered by the blockchain technology which makes them reliable and trustworthy. The virtual currency trend is now quickly growing (thanks to the blockchain technology powering it) into more than just a currency but into a trust platform for exchanging value where the virtual currency comes fully embedded within the platform ( like Ether for Ethereum ). The time horizon is soon (0-2 years) for early adopters but will certainly hit mainstream later (2-5 years). ## A complete change in trade The blockchain will provide a platform for exchange of value and will allow automating most services doing this today. Bitcoin was running on blockchain technology, but was (simply put) just a database listing who owns what amount of bitcoins. Blockchain technology is now evolving and powering, not only a database (to keep track of ownership of the cryptocurrency), but it can execute programmed instruction in a decentralized way. This makes it a decentralized computer that can be trusted to run specific programs (and you can trust the programs will not be tempered with). This allows creating smart contracts which can replace the need for having traditional contracts, as the contract itself is the execution of this program. The smart contract effects the logic of execution of the contract clauses. This automation, with the help of the internet of things, will bring the “middle man” cost in the service industry to be nearly null. This will enable new business models for application that would have otherwise not been profitable. For example a E-lock connected to the blockchain could allow you to rent your bike. This is a quite disrupting trend as it has the potential to totally revolutionize the world of finance governing at the moment. But it is also a huge opportunity to create more value and change society as we know it. ## Driven by the financial sector The financial sector is aware that such trend could disrupt the established system quite seriously; therefore there is currently important investment into Fintech (Finance technology) to be sure to be part of the disruption. A technology is just a tool and is very dependent on the use made from it, so such investment from the financial sector could be a mean to control and delay adoption. Regulation in the area will also play an important role to adoption. ## New ecosystem for maker sustainability The potential of blockchain technology and virtual currencies for Makers an opportunity to operate and exchange value within a virtual community. This could be a key element of creating an ecosystem for maker sustainability. An ecosystem that makes it easy for each maker contributing to a certain project (open source or not), not knowing if it will ever commercialise, to get not only the credit for the work but also paid. Today reserved to a limited crowd, virtual currencies could become a new money reference and be used by mainstream users (everyone) in the later future. For companies such technology could reduce many cost while bringing trust for value exchange.

SubCategories.Description:
Laminated Object Manufacturing (LOM)
Layers of paper, plastic or metal foil is glued together and cut by a knife or laser. This technology is not widely used though it is quite simple, mainly due to limited geometrical freedom - compared to other types of 3D printers.
Synonyms: Selective Deposition Laminiation (SDL)

Cladding
Cladding is combining the basics of FDM in term of a moving print head with LM in term of strength. The print head is usually moved in multiple dimensions e.g. combined with a 5-axis cnc or on a robot arm. The 5 axis CNC platform allow alternately machining and fabrication and the robot arm allow manufacturing of extraordinary large parts. Both techniques enables deposition in all direction and is not restricted to solely Z-direction. The printhead deposits melted material on a solidified surface. The feedstock can be either metal wire or powder, which is melted by an electronic beam or a laser.
Synonyms: Laser Cladding, Directed Energy Deposition (DED), Laser Metal Deposition, Laser Engineered Net Shaping (LENS)

Material Jetting (MJ)
For this technology, all material is extruded from a printhead, in contrast to BJ, but stil similar with a injektion print head.
